Lab10 Madlib	 

A Madlib is a pre-written story with blanks for missing words. Users
fill in the words without any context of how they fit into the story. 
Then you read the story. 
This can be funny (for 7 year olds) when they see what nonsense theyâ€™ve made.

Version 1

Make up or find a story, just a 2 or 3 sentences will do.

Identify 3 or 4 key words, to be replaced by user input.

Write a program that has blanks for users to enter replacements
for the key words.  Typically you have to tell the user what
part of speech the word is, so that the story at least reads ok.

When the user has typed the replacements, they should be able to
hit a button that shows the story (with the new words).  

example:

Choose an animal: elephant
Choose a place: Africa
Enter a number: 7
Name a thing: pencils
<go>
When I was in Africa, I bought a pet elephant.
I traded 7 pencils to get the elephant.

